In Java, the `==` operator is used to compare the reference (memory address) of two objects, not their values. This means that if you have two strings with the same value, but different references, they will be considered different by the `==` operator.

On the other hand, the `.equals()` method compares the values of two objects. In the case of strings, this means comparing the characters in the string.

It's generally recommended to use the `.equals()` method when comparing strings in Java, rather than the `==` operator. The `==` operator can be misleading and can lead to bugs in your code.

Here's an example to illustrate the difference:
```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";

if (str1 == str2) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are the same");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are different");
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are the same");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are different");
}
```
In this example, both `str1` and `str2` have the same value, but they have different references, so the `==` operator will consider them different. However, the `.equals()` method will correctly compare the values of the two strings and print "str1 and str2 are the same".

In summary, it's generally recommended to use the `.equals()` method when comparing strings in Java, rather than the `==` operator. The `==` operator can be misleading and can lead to bugs in your code.

